trawberry, El Dorado County, California|Strawberry CA]] || [http://troop-1.com/camp-cody/ Active] ||  Founded in 1937, run by Troop 1 of the Golden Empire Council.\n |-\n | [[Camp Crescent M]] || San Francisco Council  ||  Lake Tenaya, Yosemite  ||  Closed  ||1927\u20131962.  High adventure camp.  Non permanent.\n|-\n|Camp David Wortman\n|Sequoia Council\n|Badger\n|Active\n|\n|-\n | [[Camp Dimond-O]] ||  Oakland Area Council / San Francisco Bay Area Council  ||  Mather, CA  ||[http://www.sfbac-history.org/DimondO.html Closed]  ||1926\u20131978.  Located outside of Yosemite.\n |-\n | [[Camp Dimond]] ||  Oakland Area Council ||  Oakland, CA  ||[http://www.sfbac-history.org/Dimond.html Closed]  ||1919\u20131948. Located at the head of Dimond Canyon in Oakland.  The property was sold to the Oakland Public Schools.  Currently Joaquin Miller Elementary School and Montera Middle School occupy the site.\n |-\n | [[Camp Ed Barrer]] || Pacific Skyline Council || [[Avery, California|Avery]] || Closed ||\n |-\n | [[Camp Emerald Bay]] || Western Los Angeles County Council ||[[Emerald Bay, Catalina Island|Emerald Bay]] ||[https://www.campemeraldbay.org/ Active]|| Has been operating since 1925.\n |-\n | [[Camp Emerson]] || California Inland Empire Council || [[Idyllwild-Pine Cove, California|Idyllwild-Pine Cove]] ||[http://www.bsa-ciec.org/openrosters/view_homepage.aspx?orgkey=1907 Active]|| Operated since 1919.\n |-\n | [[Camp Fiesta Island]] || San Diego- Imperial Council || [[San Diego, California|San Diego]] ||[http://camping.sdicbsa.org/SummerPrograms/CFISummerCamp.php Active]||\n |-\n | [[Camp Fleischmann]] || Nevada Area Council || [[Chester, California|Chester]] ||[https://www.nevadabsa.org/camping/camp-fleischmann/camp-fleischmann-home/64013 Active]||\n |-\n | [[Camp Mabel French|Camp French]] || Los Padres Council || [[Arroyo Grande, California|Arroyo Grande]] || Closed ||Closed in 2014\n |-\n | [[Camp Harvey West]] || [[Golden Empire Council]] ||[[Echo Lake (California)]]  || Closed || Located on Upper Echo Lake at 7,500 feet in the [[Eldorado National Forest]] near the [[Desolation Wilderness]]. A summer camp, it had 12 troop campsites, and a staff of around 30.\n |-\n | [[Camp Helendade]] || California Inland Empire Council || [[Running Springs, California|Running Springs]] || Active || Operated since 1960 and located near Running Springs, California.  It was partially burned in the California fires of October 2007. \n |-\n | [[Camp Herms]] || Mount Diablo Silverado Council || [[El Cerrito, California|El Cerrito]] ||[https://www.mdscbsa.org/camp-herms/ Active]||\n |-\n | [[Camp Hi-Sierra]] || Silicon Valley Monterey Bay Council || [[Long Barn, California|Long Barn]] ||[http://camphi-sierra.org/chs/ Active]|| Located in the Sierra Nevada Mountain Range. This camp is at a notably high altitude, with the majority of its buildings standing at approximately 4,800 feet and the highest point of the mountain standing over a mile high at 5,300 feet.\n |-\n | [[Camp Isom]] || Greater Yosemite Council || [[Orestimba Creek]] || [http://www.yosemitescouting.org/camping/camp-isom/51469 Active] ||\n |-\n | [[Camp John Mensinger]] || Greater Yosemite Council || [[Stanislaus National Forest]]  || [http://www.yosemitescouting.org/camping/camp-john-mensinger/51466 Active] ||\n|-\n | [[Camp Josepho]] || Western Los Angeles County Council || ||[http://www.campjosepho.org/boy-scout-programs/ Active]|| Opened in 1941, the 110-acre camp is located in the Santa Monica Mountains in Los Angeles County.\n |-\n | [[Camp Kern]] || [[Southern Sierra Council]] || [[Huntington Lake]] || [http://www.sscbsa.org/campkern Active] ||\n |-\n | [[Camp Kit Carson]] || Pacific Skyline Council || [[Avery, California|Caples Lake]] || Closed ||\n |-\n | [[Camp Lassen]] || Golden Empire Council  || [[Butte Meadows, California|Butte Meadows]] || [http://www.gec-bsa.org/camping/camplassen Active] ||\n |-\n | [[Camp Lindblad]] || Mount Diablo Silverado Council || [[Boulder Creek, California|Boulder Creek]] || Closed || Sold in 2017\n |-\n | [[Camp Lilienthal - Marin]] ||  San Francisco Council / San Francisco Bay Area Council  ||  Fairfax, CA  ||[http://www.sfbac-history.org/LilienthalM-overview.html Closed]  ||1929\u20131973. First all weather camp of the SF Council.\n |-\n | [[Camp Lilienthal - SF]] ||[[San Francisco Council]]|| San Francisco, California ||[http://www.sfbac-history.org/SFC-Lilienthal.html Closed]  ||1919\u20131925. Located in Stern Grove next to Pine Lake.\n |-\n | [[Camp Loomer]] ||  Oakland Area Council / San Francisco Bay Area Council  ||  Pollack Pines, California  ||[http://www.sfbac-history.org/Loomer.html Closed]  ||1957\u20131973. \n |-\n | [[Camp I-Yee-Que]] ||[[Redwood Area Council]]|| Near Santa Rosa || Closed ||\n |-\n | [[Camp Marin-Sierra]] ||[[Marin Council|Marlin Council]]||[[Nevada City, California|Tahoe National Forest]] ||[http://www.boyscouts-marin.org/camping-programs-and-facilities/camp-marin-sierra/4056 Active]||\n |-\n | [[Camp McConnell]] ||[[Greater Yosemite Council]]||[[Livingston, California|Livingston]]  || [http://www.yosemitescouting.org/camping/camp-mcconnell/51468 Active] ||\n |-\n | [[Camp Meek]] ||[[Oakland Area Council (California)|Oakland Area Council]]|| San Lorenzo, California ||[http://www.sfbac-history.org/Meek.html Closed]  ||1942\u20131952. Located across the street from current San Lorenzo High School. \n |-\n | [[Camp Minkalo]] ||[[Greater Yosemite Council]]||[[Amador County, California|Amador County]] || Closed ||\n |-\n |[[Camp Miramichi|Camp Mirimichi]]||  ||  ||  ||\n |-\n | [[Camp Nejedly]] ||  ||  ||  ||\n |-\n | [[Camp Masonite Navarro]] ||[[Redwood Empire Council]]||  || Closed || Sold in 2012. Located near Navarro in Mendocino County, CA.\n |-\n | [[Camp Myford]] ||[[Orange County Council]]||Irvine\n| Closed || \n |-\n | [[Camp Noyo]] ||[[Redwood Empire Council]]||  || Active || Located on the Noyo River in Mendocino County, CA.  Currently Privately owned\n |-\n | [