nservancy in the early 1970s and is now part of Duck Lake State Park. Gerald R. Ford was a camp staff member there in 1927\u201328.\n|-\n| [[Camp Silver Lake]] || Detroit Area Council ||  || Sold ||\n |-\n | [[Camp T. Ben Johnston]] || [[Southwest Michigan Council]] (Michigan Crossroads Council)|| [[Augusta, Michigan|Augusta]]  || Sold || Closed in the 1980s and reverted to the W. K. Kellogg Foundation. It now operates as Sherman Lake YMCA camp.\n |-\n | [[Camp Tapico]] || Michigan Crossroads Council || [[Kalkaska, Michigan|Kalkaska]] || [https://web.archive.org/web/20141020031658/http://www.michiganscouting.org/Camping/CampTapico/ closed] || Camp Tapico is located in the eastern region of Kalkaska County just north of M-72 between Grayling and Traverse City. Sold and closed.\n |-\n | [[Camp Teetonkah]] || Michigan Crossroads Council || [[Jackson, Michigan|Jackson]] || [https://web.archive.org/web/20130122053250/http://www.michiganscouting.org/Camping/CampTeetonkah/ Active] ||\n |-\n | [[Camp Wabaningo]] || Evanston North Shore Area Council ([[Northeast Illinois Council]]) || [[Whitehall, Michigan|Whitehall]] || Sold || Closed and sold after the Evanston Council and Northshore Area Council merged in 1969.\n |-\n | [[Camp Weidman]] || Water and Woods Field Service Council || || Active || Located four miles west of Mt. Pleasant, just off M-20. \n |-\n | Camp Wilderness ||  || [[Bridgman, Michigan|Bridgman]] || Sold || Land was purchased by Rotary Club of Oak Park\u2013River Forest (IL) and donated to their local Scout council in the 1920s.  In 1945 it was sold to the State of Michigan and became part of [[Warren Dunes State Park]].<ref>{{cite magazine |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=2010-04-14 |title=Scouting, Rotary have long history in Oak Park |url=https://www.clubrunner.ca/Data/6450/4371/html/88140/RAZZ_APR_14_2010.pdf |magazine=The Rotary Razz |location= |publisher=Rotary Club of Oak Park \u2013 River Forest, IL |access-date=2020-02-10 }}</ref>\