on County, TX || Sold || Sold in the early 2010s.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.chron.com/news/houston-texas/article/Boy-Scouts-councils-turn-over-camps-forests-for-1743400.php|last=Kamb|first=Lewis|date=28 March 2013|title=Boy Scouts councils turn over camps, forests for profit|website=Chron|accessdate=21 July 2019}}</ref>\n |-\n | [[Camp Billy Gibbons]] || Texas Trails Council || Richland Springs, TX || Active ||\n |-\n | [[Camp Constantin]] || Circle Ten Council || Graford, TX || Active || Includes the Jack Furst Aquatics Base.\n |-\n | [[Camp Don Harrington]] || Golden Spread Council || Canyon, TX || Active ||\n |-\n | [[Camp Fawcett]] || Texas Southwest Council || Edwards County, TX || || Texas Southwest Council has recently leased the camp to a Houston-based hunting group.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sanangelolive.com/news/san-angelo/2017-11-09/san-angelo-boy-scouts-get-sued-over-control-historic-scouting-camp|last=Jyde|first=Joe|date=9 November 2017|title=San Angelo Boy Scouts Get Sued Over Control of Historic Scouting Camp|website=San Angelo Live!|accessdate=21 July 2019}}</ref>\n |-\n | [[Camp Hudson]] || Sam Houston Area Council || Houston, TX || Sold || Operated from 1925 to 1973.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hudsonoakstownhomessection2.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/Remembering-Camp-Hudson-%E2%80%93-%E2%80%9CA-Camping-We-Went%E2%80%9D-Villages-Magazine-by-Nancy-Loftis-July-1991.pdf|last=Loftis|first=Nancy|date=July 1991|title=A Camping We Went|publisher=Villages Magazine|accessdate=21 July 2019}}</ref>\n |-\n | [[James Ray Scout Reservation]] || Circle Ten Council || Sherman, TX || Active || Formerly known as Camp Grayson.\n |-\n | [[Camp Karankawa]] || Bay Area Councils || Sweeny, TX || Active ||\n |-\n | [[Camp M.K. Brown]] || Golden Spread Council || Mobeetie, TX || Active ||\n |-\n | [[Camp Perry]] || Rio Grande Council || Rio Hondo, TX || Active || Has operated continuously since 1927.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kveo.com/news/local-news/oldest-scouting-camp-unveils-new-dining-hall/|date=14 November 2019|title=Oldest Scouting Camp Unveils New Dining Hall|website=KVEO|accessdate=21 July 2019}}</ref>\n |-\n | [[Camp Pirtle]] || East Texas Area Council || Carthage, TX || Active ||\n |-\n | [[Camp Sol Mayer]] || Concho Valley Council || Menard, TX || Sold ||\n |-\n | [[Camp Strake]] || Sam Houston Council || Coldspring, TX || Sold || Sold in 2007 due to highway expansion.<ref name=\"auto2\"/> Reopening in 2020\n |-\n | [[Camp Tahuaya]] || Longhorn Council || Belton, TX || Active||\n |-\n | [[Camp Tom Wooten]] || Capitol Area Council || Bastrop, TX || Active || The original Camp Tom Wooten operated as a Boy Scout summer camp from 1934 until its sale in 1983. The new location operates as a camp for Cub Scouts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://westtexasscoutinghistory.net/CTW/index.html|title=Camp Tom Wooten on Bull Creek|website=West Texas Scouting History|accessdate=21 July 2019}}</ref>\n |-\n | [[Camp Tonkawa]] || Texas Trails Council || Taylor County, TX || Active ||\n |-\n | [[Camp Wisdom]] || Circle Ten Council || Dallas, TX || Active ||\n |-\n | [[Camp Zach White]] || Yucca Council ||  || Sold ||\n |-\n | [[Chisholm Trail High Adventure Base]] || Longhorn Council || Bridgeport, TX || Active || Also known as the Texas High Adventure Base.\n |-\n | [[Clements Scout Reservation]] || Circle Ten Council || Athens, TX || Active || Consists of Camp Cherokee and Camp Meisenbach.\n |-\n | [[C.W. Post Memorial Camp]] || South Plains Council || Post, TX || Active ||\n |-\n | [[El Rancho Cima]] || Sam Houston Area Council || Hays County, TX and Comal County, TX || Sold || Included Cockrell River Camp. Sold in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statesman.com/NEWS/20180315/Boy-Scouts-selling-historic-El-Rancho-Cima|last=Brown|first=Connor|date=15 March 2018|title=Boy Scouts selling historic El Rancho Cima|website=Austin American-Statesman|accessdate=21 July 2019}}</ref>\n |-\n | [[George W. Pirtle Scout Rese