om/camp-cody/ Active] ||  Founded in 1937, run by Troop 1 of the Golden Empire Council.\n |-\n | [[Camp Crescent M]] || San Francisco Council  ||  Lake Tenaya, Yosemite  ||  Closed  ||1927\u20131962.  High adventure camp.  Non permanent.\n|-\n|Camp David Wortman\n|Sequoia Council\n|Badger\n|Active\n|\n|-\n | [[Camp Dimond-O]] ||  Oakland Area Council / San Francisco Bay Area Council  ||  Mather, CA  ||[http://www.sfbac-history.org/DimondO.html Closed]  ||1926\u20131978.  Located outside of Yosemite.\n |-\n | [[Camp Dimond]] ||  Oakland Area Council ||  Oakland, CA  ||[http://www.sfbac-history.org/Dimond.html Closed]  ||1919\u20131948. Located at the head of Dimond Canyon in Oakland.  The property was sold to the Oakland Public Schools.  Currently Joaquin Miller Elementary School and Montera Middle School occupy the site.\n |-\n | [[Camp Ed Barrer]] || Pacific Skyline Council || [[Avery, California|Avery]] || Closed ||\n |-\n | [[Camp Emerald Bay]] || Western Los Angeles County Council ||[[Emerald Bay, Catalina Island|Emerald Bay]] ||[https://www.campemeraldbay.org/ Active]|| Has been operating since 1925.\n |-\n | [[Camp Emerson]] || California Inland Empire Council || [[Idyllwild-Pine Cove, California|Idyllwild-Pine Cove]] ||[http://www.bsa-ciec.org/openrosters/view_homepage.aspx?orgkey=1907 Active]|| Operated since 1919.\n |-\n | [[Camp Fiesta Island]] || San Diego- Imperial Council || [[San Diego, California|San Diego]] ||[http://camping.sdicbsa.org/SummerPrograms/CFISummerCamp.php Active]||\n |-\n | [[Camp Fleischmann]] || Nevada Area Council || [[Chester, California|Chester]] ||[https://www.nevadabsa.org/camping/camp-fleischmann/camp-fleischmann-home/64013 Active]||\n |-\n | [[Camp Mabel French|Camp French]] || Los Padres Council || [[Arroyo Grande, California|Arroyo Grande]] || Closed ||Closed in 2014\n |-\n | [[Camp Harvey West]] || [[Golden Empire Council]] ||[[Echo Lake (California)]]  || Closed || Located on Upper Echo Lake at 7,500 feet in the [[Eldorado National Forest]] near the [[Desolation Wilderness]]. A summer camp, it had 12 troop campsites, and a staff of around 30.\n |-\n | [[Camp Helendade]] || California Inland Empire Council || [[Running Springs, California|Running Springs]] || Active || Operated since 1960 and located near Running Springs, California.  It was partially burned in the California fires of October 2007. \n |-\n | [[Camp Herms]] || Mount Diablo Silverado Council || [[El Cerrito, California|El Cerrito]] ||[https://www.mdscbsa.org/camp-herms/ Active]||\n |-\n | [[Camp Hi-Sierra]] || Silicon Valley Monterey Bay Council || [[Long Barn, California|Long Barn]] ||[http://camphi-sierra.org/chs/ Active]|| Located in the Sierra Nevada Mountain Range. This camp is at a notably high altitude, with the majority of its buildings standing at approximately 4,800 feet and the highest point of the mountain standing over a mile high at 5,300 feet.\n |-\n | [[Camp Isom]] || Greater Yosemite Council || [[Orestimba Creek]] || [http://www.yosemitescouting.org/camping/camp-isom/51469 Active] ||\n |-\n | [[Camp John Mensinger]] || Greater Yosemite Council || [[Stanislaus National Forest]]  || [http://www.yosemitescouting.org/camping/camp-john-mensinger/51466 Active] ||\n|-\n | [[Camp Josepho]] || Western Los Angeles County Council || ||[http://www.campjosepho.org/boy-scout-programs/ Active]|| Opened in 1941, the 110-acre camp is located in the Santa Monica Mountains in Los Angeles County.\n |-\n | [[Camp Kern]] || [[Southern Sierra Council]] || [[Huntington Lake]] || [http://www.sscbsa.org/campkern Active] ||\n |-\n | [[Camp Kit Carson]] || Pacific Skyline Council || [[Avery, California|Caples Lake]] || Closed ||\n |-\n | [[Camp Lassen]] || Golden Empire Council  || [[Butte Meadows, California|Butte Meadows]] || [http://www.gec-bsa.org/camping/camplassen Active] ||\n |-\n | [[Camp Lindblad]] || Mount Diablo Silverado Council || [[Boulder Creek, California|Boulder Creek]] || Closed || Sold in 2017\n |-\n | [[Camp Lilienthal - Marin]] ||  San Francisco Council / San Francisco Bay Area Council  ||  Fairfax, CA  ||[http://www.sfbac-history.org/LilienthalM-overview.html Closed]  ||1929\u20131973. First all weather camp of the SF Council.\n |-\n | [[Camp Lilienthal - SF]] ||[[San Francisco Council]]|| San Francisco, California ||[http://www.sfbac-history.org/SFC-Lilienthal.html Closed]  ||1919\u20131925. Located in Stern Grove next to Pine Lake.\n |-\n | [[Camp Loomer]] ||  Oakland Area Council / San Francisco Bay Area Council  ||  Pollack Pines, California  ||[http://www.sfbac-history.org/Loomer.html Closed]  ||1957\u20131973. \n |-\n | [[Camp I-Yee-Que]] ||[[Redwood Area Council]]|| Near Santa Rosa || Closed ||\n |-\n | [[Camp Marin-Sierra]] ||[[Marin Council|Marlin Council]]||[[Nevada City, California|Tahoe National Forest]] ||[http://www.boyscouts-marin.org/camping-programs-and-facilities/camp-marin-sierra/4056 Active]||\n |-\n | [[Camp McConnell]] ||[[Greater Yosemite Council]]||[[Livingston, California|Livingston]]  || [http://www.yosemitescouting.org/camping/camp-mcconnell/51468 Active] ||\n |-\n | [[Camp Meek]] ||[[Oakland Area Council (California)|Oakland Area Council]]|| San Lorenzo, California ||[http://www.sfbac-history.org/Meek.html Closed]  ||1942\u20131952. Located across the street from current San Lorenzo High School. \n |-\n | [[Camp Minkalo]] ||[[Greater Yosemite Council]]||[[Amador County, California|Amador County]] || Closed ||\n |-\n |[[Camp Miramichi|Camp Mirimichi]]||  ||  ||  ||\n |-\n | [[Camp Nejedly]] ||  ||  ||  ||\n |-\n | [[Camp Masonite Navarro]] ||[[Redwood Empire Council]]||  || Closed || Sold in 2012. Located near Navarro in Mendocino County, CA.\n |-\n | [[Camp Myford]] ||[[Orange County Council]]||Irvine\n| Closed || \n |-\n | [[Camp Noyo]] ||[[Redwood Empire Council]]||  || Active || Located on the Noyo River in Mendocino County, CA.  Currently Privately owned\n |-\n | [[Camp Okihi]] ||  ||  ||[https://www.campokihi.org/ Active]||\n |-\n | [[Camp Oljato]] ||[[Pacific Skyline Council]]||Lakeshore, CA\n|[http://campoljato.com/ Active]|| Located at Huntington Lake in Lakeshore, CA, and was founded in 1941 as a Jewish boys' singing camp.\n |-\n | [[Camp Pacifico|Camp Pacifica]] ||  ||[[Ahwahnee, California|Ahwahnee]]\n|Closed\n|Currently a Lions Club camp\n |-\n | [[Camp Pahatsi]] ||[[Golden Empire Council]]||[[Soda Springs, Nevada County, California|Soda Springs]] || [https://web.archive.org/web/20120329181433/http://www.gec-bsa.org/camping/campcole Active] ||\n |-\n | [[Camp Pico Blanco]] || [[Silicon Valley Monterey Bay Council]] || [[Big Sur, California|Big Sur]]||[http://camppicoblanco.org/pico/ Active] ||\n |-\n | [[Camp Pollock]] ||[[Golden Empire Council]]||[[Sacramento, California|Sacramento]] ||[http://www.sacramentovalleyconservancy.org/camp-pollock.asp Closed]  ||Sold to the Sacramento Valley Conservancy. \n |-\n | [[Camp Pomponio]] ||  ||  ||  ||\n|-\n|Camp Riggs Johnston\n|Crate Lake Council\n|Eureka\n|[https://www.craterlakecouncil.org/activities/camp-reservations/camp-riggs/ Active]\n|Formerly Elk River Scout Camp\n|-\n | [[Camp Rokili]] ||[[Orange County Council]]||  || Closed || \n |-\n | [[Camp Robert L. Cole]] ||[[Golden Empire Council]]||[[Cisco Grove, California|Cisco Grove]], CA || [https://web.archive.org/web/20120329181433/http://www.gec-bsa.org/camping/campcole Active] ||\n |-\n | [[Camp Royaneh / Camp CC Moore]] ||[[San Francisco Bay Area Council]]|| Cazadero, CA ||[http://www.sfbac-history.org/Royaneh.html Active]  ||1925\u2013present.  Camp Royaneh was renamed to Camp CC Moore in honor of SF Council President and National BSA Vice-President Charles C. Moore from 1938 until 1950.  Its name was changed back  to Camp Royaneh in 1950/1951.\n |-\n | [[Camp Silverado]] ||Silverado Area Council\n|Pioneer, CA\n|Closed\n|Closed in 2003\n|-\n |Camp Silver Fir\n |Verdugo Hills Council\n |Lakeshore\n |[https://vhcbsa.org/facilities/camp-silver-fir/ Active]\n |\n|-\n | [[Camp Stephens]] ||[[Alameda Council]]||[[Pinecrest Lake]] || Closed || \n|-\n | [[Camp Tahquitz]] ||[[Long Beach Area Council]]||[[Angelus Oaks, California|Angelus Oaks]] ||[https://www.longbeachbsa.org/aboutus/tahquitz/ Active]|| \n|-\n | [[Camp Tamarancho]]|| Marin Council || Farifax ||[http://www.boyscouts-marin.org/camping-and-facilities/camp-tamarancho/4057 Active]\n|\n |-\n | [[Camp Three Falls]] || Ventura County Council || Frazier Park ||[https://www.vccbsa.org/Camping/Camp%20Three%20Falls/ Active]\n|\n|-\n|Camp Verdugo Oaks\n|Verdugo Hills Council\n|\n|[https://vhcbsa.org/facilities/camp-verdugo-oaks/ Active]\n|\n|-\n | [[Camp Whitsett]] ||[[Western Los Angeles County Council]]||  ||[http://www.campwhitsett.org/ Active]|| Located in the Sequoia National Forest.\n |-\n | [[Camp Winton]] ||[[Golden Empire Council]]||[[Bear River Reservoir]] || [http://www.gec-bsa.org/camping/campwinton Active] ||\n |-\n | [[Camp Wolfeboro]] ||[[Mt Diablo Silverado Council]]||  ||[https://campwolfeboro.mdscbsa.org/ Active]|| located in Sierra Nevada Mountains near Angels Camp and Bear Valley. Started operating as a Boy Scout camp in 1928.\n |-\n | [[Camp Wolverton]] ||[[Western Los Angeles County Council]]||  || Closed || Located in the Sequoia National Park.\nClosed in 2012\n |-\n | [[Chesebrough Scout Reservation]] ||[[Silicon Valley Monterey Bay Council]]||  ||[http://svmbc.org/svmbc/campproperties/chesebrough-scout-reservation/ Active]|| Also called Camp Chesebrough, this is a 544-acre (2.2&nbsp;km\u00b2) Boy Scouts of America camp in the Santa Cruz Mountains of Santa Cruz and San Mateo counties, California.\n |-\n | [[Circle B Scout Ranch]] ||[[Old Baldy Area Council]]||  || Closed || Open from the late 1950s until 1974, it was located in the southern Sierra Nevada northeast of Lake Isabella and due west of China Lake Naval Weapons Station.\n |-\n | [[Camp Circle X|Circle X]] ||[[Los Angeles Area Council]]||[[Cedar Glen, California|Cedar Glen]]|| Active ||Camp Circle X at Big Horn.  Part of Hubert Eaton Scout Reservation.\n |-\n | [[Cutter Scout Reservation]] ||[[Pacific Skyline Council]]||[[Boulder Creek, California|Boulder Creek]] || Active ||\n |-\n | [[Firestone Scout Reservation]] ||[[Los Angeles Area Council]]||[[Brea, California|Brea]]  ||[https://www.glaacbsa.org/firestone Active]|| Located just east of State Route 57 in Tonner Canyon between Diamond Bar and Brea, California.\n |-\n | [[Forest Lawn Scout Reservation]]\naka Hubert Eaton Scout Reservation\n|[[Los Angeles Area Council]]||[[Lake Arrowhead, California|Lake Arrowhead]] ||[https://www.glaacbsa.org/Hubert_Eaton Active]|| Located 3 miles (5&nbsp;km) east of Lake Arrowhead, California, formerly known as the Lake Arrowhead Scout Camps. The Forest Lawn Scout Reservation consists of five active and one closed Boy and Cub Scout resident camps on more than 2,000 acres in the San Bernardino National Forest.  The six camps are:\n{|\n|-\n|\n* Circle X Ranch at Big Horn\n* Camp Pepperdine,\n* Camp Pitchess, formerly Camp Cedar (closed)\n|\n* Camp Pollock \u2013 adjacent to what was once Camp Pitchess\n* John Wayne Outpost \u2013 wilderness camping area\n* Northrop Family Camp\n|}\n |-\n | [[Glacial Trails Scout Ranch]] ||[[Golden Empire Council]]||[[Cisco Grove, California|Tahoe National Forest]] || Closed || Reopened as Camp Robert L. Cole.\n  |-\n | [[Holcomb Valley Scout Ranch]] ||[[San Gabriel Valley Council]]|| Big Bear ||[https://www.glaacbsa.org/holcomb Active]|| Located north of Big Bear Lake in the old mining district of Belleville in the Holcomb Valley, on the site of the old Hitchcock Ranch.\n |-\n | [[Holt Scout Ranch]] ||[[San Gabriel Valley Council]]||  || [http://www.lafavre.us/holt/Holt_Scout_Ranch.htm Closed] || Closed in 1974. Previously known as Camp Cedar Canyon\n |-\n | [[Irvine Ranch Outdoor Education Center]] ||[[Orange County Council]]||[[Orange, California|Orange]] ||[https://www.outdooreducationcenter.org/ Active]|| 190 Acres\n |-\n | [[Jubilee Scout Ranch]] ||[[Western Los