am]] || [[Michigan Crossroads Council]] || [[Lake Orion, Michigan|Lake Orion]] || [http://www.michiganscouting.org/pubs/MCC_Strategic_Plan_for_Camp_Properties_2014_2024.pdf Run by local parks ]{{Dead link|date=March 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} ||\n |- \n | [[Camp Brady]] || [[Detroit Area Council]] (Michigan Crossroads Council) || [[Waterford, Michigan|Waterford]] || Sold || Sold in 1946\n |-\n | [[Camp Frank S. Betz]] || [[Pathway to Adventure Council]] || [[Berrien Springs, Michigan|Berrien Springs]] || [http://www.calumetcouncil.org/CampBetz.html Active] ||\n |-\n | [[Camp Greilick]] || Michigan Crossroads Council  || [[Traverse City, Michigan|Traverse City]] || [https://web.archive.org/web/20130530072532/http://www.michiganscouting.org/Camping/CampGreilick/ Closed] |Reverted to Rotary Foundation of Traverse City||\n |-\n | [[Camp Haley]] || Summer Trails Council || [[Selkirk, Michigan|Selkirk]] || Sold || Sold in 1947. Was on Henderson Lake near [[Lupton, Michigan]]. It is now the [[Camp Lu Lay Lea]] Lutheran summer camp.\n |-\n | [[Bay-Lakes_Council#Camp_Hiawatha|Camp Hiawatha]] || [[Bay-Lakes Council]] || [[Munising, Michigan|Munising]] || [http://www.baylakesbsa.org/camping/camp-hiawatha/52143 Active] ||\n |-\n | [[Camp Highland]] ||  ||  || ||\n |-\n | [[Camp Holaka]]   || Michigan Crossroads Council  || [[Lapeer, Michigan|Lapeer]] || [http://www.michiganscouting.org/Camping/CampHolaka/ Closed] || Located on 340 acres in Lapeer County.  Camp Holaka was sold 2018.\n |-\n | [[Camp Kanesatake]] || [[Great Sauk Trail Council|Wolverine Council]] (Michigan Crossroads Council) || [[Cambridge Township, Michigan|Cambridge Township]] || Sold || The camp was located on Washington Lake. It was sold in the early 1980s.\n |-\n | [[Camp Kiroliex]] || [[Chief Okemos Council]] (Michigan Crossroads Council) || [[Waterloo Township, Michigan|Waterloo Township]] || Closed || The camp was located on Clear Lake in Waterloo Township, Michigan.\n |-\n | [[Camp Kiwanis]] || Saginaw Kiwanis Club || [[Mason, Michigan|Mason]] || [http://www.michiganscouting.org/Camping/CampKiwanis/ Closed] || 85 acres located 3.5 miles east of Mason, Michigan on M-36 at Diamond Road. \n |-\n | [[Camp Madron]] || [[Southwest Michigan Council]] (Michigan Crossroads Council)|| [[Buchanan, Michigan|Buchanan]]  || Sold || Was located on Madron Lake and sold in 1985. \n |-\n | [[Camp Mills]] ||  ||  || ||\n |-\n | [[Camp Munhacke]] || Michigan Crossroads Council || [[Gregory, Michigan|Gregory]] || [https://web.archive.org/web/20130122053239/http://www.michiganscouting.org/Camping/CampMunhacke/ Active] || Michigan Crossroads council announced in October, 2019, the camp will be closed in January, 2020.\n |-\n | [[Camp Neyati]] || [[Summer Trails/Paul Bunyan Council]] || [[Lake, Clare County, Michigan|Lake, Michigan]]  ||  Closed  ||  Closed in 1962, and is now owned and operated by Midland Community Foundation.\n |-\n | [[Camp Northwinds]] || [[Southwest Michigan Council]] (Michigan Crossroads Council)|| [[Eden Township, Mason County, Michigan|Eden Township]]  || Sold || 1,280 camp located in Mason County. Sold in 1991.\n |-\n | [[Camp Pine Lake]] || [[Tall Pine Council]] (Michigan Crossroads Council) || [[Linden, Michigan|Linden]] || Closed ||\n |-\n | [[Camp Rotary]] || Michigan Crossroads Council || [[Clare, Michigan|Clare]] || [https://web.archive.org/web/20130712174655/http://www.michiganscouting.org/Camping/CampRotary Active] || The campground is owned by the Saginaw Rotary Club, but leased by the Boy Scouts.  Camp Rotary offers 1,180 acres of year around camping just north of Clare, MI, on old US-27.\n |-\n | [[Camp Shawondasee]] || || [[Whitehall, Michigan|Whitehall]] || Closed || Originally located near West Olive (Port Sheldon) on Lake Michigan (1916\u20131927) it re-located to  Duck Lake, near Whitehall, Michigan, in 1927 the property was acquired by the Nature Conservancy in the early 1970s and is now part of Duck Lake State Park. Gerald R. Ford was a camp staff member there in 1927\u201328.\n|-\n| [[Camp Silver Lake]] || Detroit Area Council ||  || Sold ||\n |-\n | [[Camp T. Ben Johnston]] || [[Southwest Michigan Council]] (Michigan Crossroads Council)|| [[Augusta, Michigan|Augusta]]  || Sold || Closed in the 1980s and reverted to the W. K. Kellogg Foundation. It now operates as Sherman Lake YMCA camp.\n |-\n | [[Camp Tapico]] || Michigan Crossroads Council || [[Kalkaska, Michigan|Kalkaska]] || [https://web.archive.org/web/20141020031658/http://www.michiganscouting.org/Camping/CampTapico/ closed] || Camp Tapico is located in the eastern region of Kalkaska County just north of M-72 between Grayling and Traverse City. Sold and closed.\n |-\n | [[Camp Teetonkah]] || Michigan Crossroads Council || [[Jackson, Michigan|Jackson]] || [https://web.archive.org/web/20130122053250/http://www.michiganscouting.org/Camping/CampTeetonkah/ Active] ||\n |-\n | [[Camp Wabaningo]] || Evanston North Shore Area Council ([[Northeast Illinois Council]]) || [[Whitehall, Michigan|Whitehall]] || Sold || Closed and sold after the Evanston Council and Northshore Area Council merged in 1969.\n |-\n | [[Camp Weidman]] || Water and Woods Field Service Council || || Active || Located four miles west of Mt. Pleasant, just off M-20. \n |-\n | Camp Wilderness ||  || [[Bridgman, Michigan|Bridgman]] || Sold || Land was purchased by Rotary Club of Oak Park\u2013River Forest (IL) and donated to their local Scout council in the 1920s.  In 1945 it was sold to the State of Michigan and became part of [[Warren Dunes State Park]].<ref>{{cite magazine |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=2010-04-14 |title=Scouting, Rotary have long history in Oak Park |url=https://www.clubrunner.ca/Data/6450/4371/html/88140/RAZZ_APR_14_2010.pdf |magazine=The Rotary Razz |location= |publisher=Rotary Club of Oak Park \u2013 River Forest, IL |access-date=2020-02-10 }}</ref>\n |-\n | [[Charles Howell Scout Reservation]] || Detroit Area Council (Michigan Crossroads Council) || [[Brighton, Michigan|Brighton]] || Sold || Located on Brighton Lake. Sold in 1986.\n |-\n | [[Cole Canoe Base]] || Michigan Crossroads Council || [[Moffatt Township, Michigan|Alger]] || [https://web.archive.org/web/20130524151041/http://www.michiganscouting.org/Camping/ColeCanoeBase/ Active] ||\n |-\n | [[D-Bar-A Scout Ranch]] || Michigan Crossroads Council || [[Metamora, Michigan|Metamora]] || [https://web.archive.org/web/20130530071706/http://www.michiganscouting.org/Camping/D-AScoutRanch/ Active] ||\n |-\n | [[Gerber Scout Reservation]] || Michigan Crossroads Council || [[Twin Lake, Michigan|Twin Lake]] || [https://web.archive.org/web/20130716060028/http://www.michiganscouting.org/Camping/GerberScoutReservation Active] ||\n |-\n | [[Lost Lake Scout Reservation]] || Michigan Crossroads Council || [[Garfield Township, Clare County, Michigan|Lake]] || [http://www.michiganscouting.org/pubs/MCC_Strategic_Plan_for_Camp_Properties_2014_2024.pdf Closed]{{Dead link|date=March 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} || Closed in 2012.\n |-\n | [[Northwoods Scout Reservation]] || Michigan Crossroads Council || [[Lupton, Michigan|Lupton]] || [https://web.archive.org/web/20130122053311/http://www.michiganscouting.org/Camping/NorthwoodsScoutReservation/ closed] || 840 acres located near West Branch in Ogemaw County, Michigan. \n |-\n | [[Owasippe Scout Reservation]] || Chicago Area Council (Now Pathway to Adventure Council) || [[Twin Lake, Michigan|Twin Lake]] || [http://www.chicagobsa.org/camping/owasippe-scout-reservation/3820 Active] ||  4,800 acres located near Twin Lake, Michigan. Oldest Boy Scout Camp in continuous operation. Since 1911. \n |-\n | [[Paul Bunyan Scout Reservation]] || Michigan Crossroads Council || || Closed || Located on 600 acres bordering the Huron National Forest, with water activities on the AuSable River, just north of Rose City on M-33.  Paul Bunyan Scout Reservation was closed for the 2013 camping year.\n |-\n | [[Prevailing Winds II]] ||  ||  || ||\n |-\n | [[Rota-Kiwan Scout Reservation]] || Michigan Crossroads Council || [[Kalamazoo, Michigan|Kalamazoo]] || [https://web.archive.org/web/20130122053116/http://www.michiganscouting.org/Camping/RotaKiwanScoutReservation/ Active] || 199 acres located in [[Texas Charter Township, Michigan|Texas Township]] southwest of Kalamazoo. The camp also borders the 741 acre [[Al Sabo Preserve]], which provides numerous hiking triais. The Boy Scout resident camp is Camp Madron and the Cub Scout resident camp is Camp T. Ben Johnston. Both are named after former camps of the Southwest Michigan Council that were sold in the 1980s. Council announced in October, 2019, that the camp would close in January, 2020.\n |-\n | [[Silver Trails Scout Reservation]] || Michigan Crossroads Council || [[Jeddo, Michigan|Jeddo]] || [https://web.archive.org/web/20140331010654/http://www.michiganscouting.org/Camping/SilverTrailsScoutReservation/ Closed and sold] || Located near Jeddo, Michigan, south of Croswell, and about 15 miles (24&nbsp;km) northwest of Port Huron.\n |-\n | [[Wolverine Council Summer Camp]] ||  ||  || ||\n |-\n | [[Wood Lake Scout Reservation]] || [[La Salle Council]] || [[Jones, Michigan|Jones]] || [https://web.archive.org/web/20140701022148/http://www.lasallecouncilbsa.org/Camps/Wood%20Lake%20Scout%20Reservation%20-%20Camp%20Tamarack Active] || [[Camp Tamarack, Indiana|Camp Tamarack]] is located at Wood Lake Scout Reservation.\n\n|}\n\n=== Minnesota ===\n{{Details|Scouting in Minnesota}}\n {| class=\"wikitable sortable\" border=\"1\" width=\"100%\"\n |-\n ! scope=\"col\" width=\"30%\" | Camp name\n ! scope=\"col\" width=\"20%\" | Council\n ! scope=\"col\" width=\"15%\" | Location\n ! scope=\"col\" width=\"10%\" | Status\n ! scope=\"col\" width=\"25%\"  class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n | [[Camp Clyde]] ||  ||  || ||\n |-\n | [[Camp Hoksila]] ||  ||  || ||\n |-\n | [[Camp Neibel]] ||  ||  || ||\n |-\n | [[Camp Norseland]] ||  ||  || ||\n |-\n | [[Camp Wabaunaquat]] || Formerly Lake Agassiz Council || Near Ogema, MN || Inactive || Operated from 1940 to 1980; located near the [[White Earth Indian Reservation]].\n |-\n | [[Camp Wichingen]] || Headwaters Area Council || || Active || Located south of Hibbing, Minnesota.\n |-\n | [[Camp Wilderness]] || Northern Lights Council || Park Rapids, MN || Active||The 2,400 acre \"Outdoor Classroom\" is situated between beautiful Bad Axe and Mantrap Lake near Park Rapids, MN in Hubbard County. \n |-\n | [[Cannon River Scout Reservation]] ||  ||  || ||Renamed Phillippo Scout Reservation\n |-\n | [[Charles L. Sommers Canoe Base]] || National BSA Council || Near Ely, MN || Active || One of the three bases operated by Northern Tier High Adventure programs that offers canoe treks in the boundary waters of Northern Minnesota, southwest Ontario, and southeast Manitoba.\n |-\n | [[Crow Wing Scout Reservation]] ||  ||  || ||\n |-\n | [[Cuyuna Scout Camp]] || Twin Valley Council || Cross Lake, MN || Active||Cuyuna Scout Camp is located in a heavily wooded area approximately 30 miles north of Brainerd, MN and 4 miles north of Crosslake, MN on HWY 3.\n\nThe camp is 684 acres and borders on six lakes.\n |-\n | [[Kiwanis Scout Reservation]] || Northern Star Council || || [https://web.archive.org/web/20130630024332/http://camping.nsbsa.org/Camps/Kiwanis.aspx Active] || 110 acres located on the banks of the St. Croix River near St. Croix. This was a youth camp starting in 1925, and became a Scout camp in 1989.\n |-\n | [[Many Point Scout Camp]] || Northern Star Area Council || || [https://web.archive.org/web/20130630023649/http://camping.nsbsa.org/Camps/ManyPoint.aspx Active] || 2,400 acres located in Ponsford, Minnesota. It has been operating for over 60 years.\n |-\n | [[Base Camp]] || Northern Star Council || || [http://www.explorebasecamp.org/ Active] || Located in the century-old Cavalry Drill Hall near Fort Snelling, Minnesota.\n |-\n |[https://www.bsacmc.org/parker-scout-camp Parker Scout Reservation]||  ||  || ||Established in 1941 by Clyde Parker, Camp Parker (formerly known as Camp Clyde) sits on 256 wooded acres just north of Brainerd on North Long Lake at 21930 Paradise Drive in Nisswa, MN 56468 in Crow Wing County.\n\nCamp Parker is available year-round for use by Scout groups and non-Scout youth groups. Featuring a medieval castle, dining lodge, several camp sites and cabins, a family camp, trading post, shower house, sandy beach, gun and archery ranges, and much more!\n |-\n | [[Phillippo Scout Reservation]] || Northern Star Area Council || || [https://web.archive.org/web/20130629045945/http://camping.nsbsa.org/Camps/Phillippo.aspx Active] || Renamed in 2000, Phillippo Scout Reservation was originally called the Cannon River Scout Reservation.  Located on 450 acres near Cannon Falls, Minnesota, it opened in 1964.\n |-\n | [[Rum River Scout Camp]] || Northern Star Area Council || || [https://web.archive.org/web/20130630024337/http://camping.nsbsa.org/Camps/RumRiver.aspx Active] ||  Operating since 1957, Rum River Scout Camp is a 167-acre facility on the Rum River located 4 miles north of Anoka, Minnesota.\n |-\n | [[Stearns Scout Camp]] || Northern Star Area Council || || [https://web.archive.org/web/20130617144508/http://camping.nsbsa.org/Camps/Stearns.aspx Active] || 1,200 acres located near South Haven, Minnesota.\n|}\n\n=== Mississippi ===\n{{Details|Scouting in Mississippi}}\n {| class=\"wikitable sortable\" border=\"1\" width=\"100%\"\n |-\n ! scope=\"col\" width=\"30%\" | Camp name\n ! scope=\"col\" width=\"20%\" | Council\n ! scope=\"col\" width=\"15%\" | Location\n ! scope=\"col\" width=\"10%\" | Status\n ! scope=\"col\" width=\"25%\"  class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n |-\n | [[Camp Binachi]] || Choctaw Area Council ||  Meridian, MS  ||  Active  ||\n |-\n | [[Chickasaw Council#Camp Currier|Camp Currier]] || Chickasaw Council || Eudora, MS || Active ||\n |-\n | [[Camp Kickapoo]] || Last Frontier Council || Hinds County