yon Camp]] ||  ||  || ||\n |-\n | [[Cascade Pacific Council Challenge Program]] ||  Cascade Pacific Council  ||  || ||\n |-\n | [[Cub World]] || Cascade Pacific Council || Happy Valley, OR || Closed || Closed in 2015 after Scouters' Mountain property was sold.\n |-\n | [[Gilbert Ranch (cub)]] ||  Cascade Pacific Council  ||  || Active  ||  Butte Creek Scout Ranch's summer program\n |-\n | [[Scouter\u2019s Mountain]] ||  Cascade Pacific Council  ||  ||  Closed || Sold in 2015.\n|}\n\n=== Pennsylvania ===\n{{Details|Scouting in Pennsylvania}}\n {| class=\"wikitable sortable\" border=\"1\" width=\"100%\"\n |-\n ! scope=\"col\" width=\"30%\" | Camp name\n ! scope=\"col\" width=\"20%\" | Council\n ! scope=\"col\" width=\"15%\" | Location\n ! scope=\"col\" width=\"10%\" | Status\n ! scope=\"col\" width=\"25%\"  class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n |-\n | [[Allegheny Trails Scout Camps]] ||  ||  || ||\n |-\n | [[Anawanna Scout Reservation]] || Laurel Highlands Council ||  || ||\n |-\n | [[Bashore Scout Reservation]] || Pennsylvania Dutch Council ||  Jonestown, PA\n| Active\n|\n |-\n | [[Breyer Training Area]] || Philadelphia Council || [[Cheltenham Township, Pennsylvania|Cheltenham]] || Closed || In 1929, [[Henry W. Breyer, Jr.]], purchased the abandoned Lindenhurst property once owned by [[John Wanamaker]] in [[Cheltenham Township, Pennsylvania|Cheltenham]] on York Road, below Washington Lane. Breyer donated the former Wanamaker land to the Boy Scouts of America for use as a wildlife preserve.<ref name=\"bryer\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.livingplaces.com/PA/Montgomery_County/Cheltenham_Township.html|title=Cheltenham Township, Montgomery County, Pennsylvania (PA)|website=www.livingplaces.com}}</ref> The camp was accessible to city Scouts by taking the train to the [[Jenkintown-Wyncote (SEPTA station)|Jenkintown station]]. Camp Henry W. Breyer ({{Coord|40.0853|N|75.1311|W}}) was sold by the Philadelphia Council in 1990 and is now the site of [[Salus University]].\n |-\n | [[Northeastern Pennsylvania Council|Camp Acahela]] || Northeastern Pennsylvania Council || Blakeslee, PA || Active || This 242-acre camp was founded in 1919 and has offered an annual Cub Scout Resident camping program since 1992.  It is located near the confluence of the Lehigh River and the Tobyhanna Creek.\n |-\n | [[Camp Brule]] ||  ||  || ||\n |-\n | [[Camp Bucoco]] || Moraine Trails Council ||  || ||\n |-\n | [[Camp Chickasaw]] ||  ||  || ||\n |-\n | [[Camp Chiquetan]] ||  ||  || ||\n |-\n | [[Camp Coffman]] || Colonel Drake Council || Oil City, PA || Closed ||\n |-\n | [[Camp Conewago]] || New Birth of Freedom Council ||  || ||\n |-\n | [[Camp Ganoga]] || York-Adams Area Council ||  || Closed ||  Closed in 1945.  Replaced by Camp Tuckahoe. \n |-\n | [[Camp Karoondinha]] ||  ||  || ||\n |-\n | [[Camp Kiondashawa]] || Mercer County Council || Sharon, PA || Closed  ||  Closed.  Replaced by Custaloga Town Scout Reservation.\n |-\n | [[Camp Kline]] ||  ||  || ||\n |-\n | [[Camp Lavigne]] ||  ||  || ||\n |-\n | [[Camp Minsi]] || [[Minsi Trails Council]] || [[Pocono Summit, Pennsylvania]] || [http://www.campminsi.org/ Active] || Founded in 1949, the 1,200-acre Boy Scout camp is located off of Pennsylvania Route 940 along the shores of the 314-acre [[Stillwater Lake (Pennsylvania)|Stillwater Lake]] in Pocono Summit.\n |-\n | [[Camp Mountain Run]] || Bucktail Council || DuBois, Pennsylvania || Active ||\n |-\n | [[Camp Olmsted (Pennsylvania)|Camp Olmsted]] || Chief Cornplanter Council || Warren, Pennsylvania || Active ||\n |-\n | [[Camp Rotawanis]] || Hazleton Area Council || Drums, Pennsylvania || Closed || Closed as a council Boy Scout camp in 1970s after Hazleton area merged with Minsi Trails Council. Occasional Scout unit camping and hiking events are conducted on site. Non-Scouting camping/hiking is also conducted.\n |-\n | [[Camp Semiconon]] ||  ||  || ||\n |-\n | [[Camp Seph Mack]] || Laurel Highlands Council || Penn Run, Pennsylvania || ||\n |-\n | [[Camp Sequoyah]] 